etymologies: Old English prīm (in prime (sense 2 of the noun)), from Latin prima (hora) ‘first (hour)’, reinforced in Middle English by Old French prime; the adjective dates from late Middle English, via Old French from Latin primus ‘first’

definitions: of first importance; main

examples.text: her prime concern is the well-being of the patient

definitions: from which another thing may derive or proceed

examples.text: Diogenes' conclusion that air is the prime matter

shortDefinitions: from which something else may derive

definitions: of the best possible quality; excellent

examples.text: a prime site in the center of Indianapolis

definitions: having all the expected or typical characteristics of something

examples.text: the novel is a prime example of the genre

definitions: most suitable or likely

examples.text: it's the prime contender for best comedy of the year

definitions: (of a number) evenly divisible only by itself and one (e.g., 2, 3, 5, 7, 11).
shortDefinitions: divisible only by itself and one

definitions: (of two or more numbers in relation to each other) having no common factor but one

examples.text: a congruence whose modulus is a number prime to b

shortDefinitions: having no common factor but one

definitions: a state or time of greatest strength, vigor, or success in a person's life

examples.text: you're in the prime of life
he wasn't elderly, but clearly past his prime

definitions: the beginning or first period of something
a service forming part of the Divine Office, traditionally said (or chanted) at the first hour of the day (i.e., 6 a.m.), but now little used.
a prime number.
a symbol (ʹ) written after a letter or symbol as a distinguishing mark or after a figure as a symbol for minutes or feet.
the first of eight standard parrying positions.

etymologies: early 16th century (in the sense ‘fill, load’): origin uncertain; probably based on Latin primus ‘first’, since the sense expressed is a ‘first’ operation prior to something else

definitions: make (something) ready for use or action.
shortDefinitions: make ready for use or action

definitions: prepare (a firearm or explosive device) for firing or detonation

examples.text: he grabbed a gun from a nearby wall and primed it

definitions: cover (a surface) with a preparatory coat of paint in order to prevent the absorption of subsequent layers of paint

examples.text: prime the new timber before painting the sill

definitions: pour or spray liquid into (a pump) before starting in order to seal the moving parts and facilitate its operation

examples.text: ensure a sufficient head of water is available to prime the pump

definitions: inject extra fuel into (the cylinder or carburetor of an internal combustion engine) in order to facilitate starting.
(of a steam engine or its boiler) mix water with the steam being passed into the cylinder.
shortDefinitions: mix water with steam being passed into cylinder

definitions: serve as a starting material for (a polymerization process)

examples.text: the oligonucleotide might prime DNA polymerase activity at multiple sites

shortDefinitions: serve as starting material for polymerization

definitions: prepare (someone) for a situation or task, typically by supplying them with relevant information

examples.text: the sentries had been primed to admit him without challenge
